2026-04-21 01:27:10 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['misconnection between control module output cables and load module input cables (polarity swapped or paired incorrectly)'] hypothesis_explanation='All module internals and cables continuity test good, and the PSU delivers a solid 12 V. Yet only ~0.36 V appears at the control‑module output and at the load input, with no polarity inversion across the control module and with the switch state having no effect. The red ‘inverted cables’ LED sits reverse‑biased (anode at 0 V, cathode at ~12 V), so the control input pair is correctly oriented with respect to the PSU. The load module likewise has correct internal wiring and the diode and lamps show nominal resistance.\n\nThe remaining plausible fault is configuration, not component failure: the fast‑connection cables between the control‑module output and the load‑module input are not paired as intended. In particular, the conductor that the control module drives as its +12 V output is not actually connected to the load module’s intended +12 V terminal; instead the two conductors between the modules are cross‑paired or otherwise swapped, so that the load’s diode sees almost no potential difference (its ‘+’ side tied effectively near ground or to the wrong node). That miswiring allows only a small leakage or measurement‑artifact voltage (~0.36 V) to appear at what we’re calling the ‘+’ line, preventing current through the series diode and lamps. Correcting the cable pairing/polarity between the control and load modules should restore full 12 V across the load and allow the lamp to operate when the switch is closed.'
