2026-04-21 01:27:19 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['incorrect internal wiring or polarity of the power‑supply indicator LED/resistor branch causing the PSU ‘−’ output to float through the LED path'] hypothesis_explanation='All series cabling and the control‑module path have been verified for continuity and correct polarity, and both load lamps and the diode path in the load cube test nominal. Yet, under load, the control‑module and load ‘+’ nodes sit at only ~0.36 V relative to the reference used for all earlier measurements, while the PSU green LED is lit and the indicator branch in the control module sees ~12 V across it. This strongly suggests that the reference being used as “0 V” in the rest of the system is not actually tied solidly to the negative of the 12 V supply under load, but is instead being biased through a high‑impedance path. The only remaining component that can create such a condition, given the verified continuity of the negative cable itself and of all other branches, is a miswired or incorrectly oriented PSU indicator LED/resistor network that connects between the nominal +12 V and some node other than the true PSU negative/ground. In that case the lamp and control module are referenced to a floating node pulled weakly toward +12 V via the LED branch, producing a small apparent voltage (~0.36 V) across the lamp circuit and preventing significant current flow even though the PSU LED glows. Repairing/re‑wiring the power‑supply indicator branch to connect correctly from +12 V to the true 0 V output should restore a solid reference and allow the main lamp to receive the full 12 V when the switch is closed.'
