2026-04-21 01:27:46 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal wiring of red LED/resistor ‘inverted‑cables’ indicator branch (LED polarity reversed with respect to series path and module I/O)'] hypothesis_explanation='All series‑path conductors from PSU + to control input +, through the switch, to control output +, and on to the load module have been verified for continuity and correct polarity; the PSU negative reference and all − cables are solid at 0 V. Yet with the switch ON, the control output (+) and the cable onward to the load sit at only ~0.36 V with respect to ground, while the PSU input (+) and the node feeding the series resistor of the indicator stay at ~12 V. The measurement on the indicator branch shows its resistor both ends at ~12 V, the LED cathode at ~12 V, and its anode clamped at 0 V. This means the red LED is wired from ground (anode) up to the +12 V rail (cathode) in the opposite polarity to that described; it is therefore forward‑biased whenever the control input + is at 12 V and draws current from +12 V toward ground through its 1 kΩ resistor. That LED current, flowing into the common 0 V node, creates a reference at a few hundred millivolts on any point in the series path that is only weakly coupled to +12 V, which is exactly the ~0.36 V seen at the control output (+). All other paths have tested good or have been ruled out; the only element that consistently explains the observed voltages is a polarity‑reversed indicator LED branch inside the control module. Repairing the internal wiring of this red LED/resistor branch so that the LED is oriented correctly (from +12 V to 0 V as per design) will remove the unintended clamp and allow the full 12 V to appear at the control output and hence at the load so the lamp can operate normally.'
